`stroke/` is the steno-stroke encoding layer: parsing raw stroke text into bank-partitioned key sets, rendering back to canonical steno string form, and merging/subtracting keys to implement numeric "count" expansion within a stroke. Depending on this subtree gets you `parse_stroke`/`render_stroke` (keys.rs) and `CountBank`/`apply_count`/`merge_strokes`/`subtract_strokes` (bank.rs), re-exported from mod.rs.

The two files are tightly coupled through the stroke text format: bank.rs calls `parse_stroke`/`render_stroke` on every operation, so any change to key-bank membership, hyphen rules, or the left/mid/right ordering in keys.rs directly changes what strokes bank.rs can merge or reject. Canonical order is fixed: `# | S T K P W H R | A O * E U | F R P B L G T S D Z`; `render_stroke` always re-sorts to this order regardless of input order, and the hyphen appears only when right-bank keys exist with no middle key present. Because of this, keys.rs's parse→render is not always an identity round-trip on the literal input string — bank.rs and any other caller must expect canonical re-formatting, not string preservation.

`R` is ambiguous between left and right bank and resolved only by hyphen position or phase-scan order — a fact bank.rs is not itself aware of; it assumes keys.rs already resolved bank membership when merging/subtracting key sets. `merge_strokes`/`add_key` error on any key collision, and `subtract_strokes` returns `None` (not an error) when the subtrahend isn't a subset — callers distinguish "already present" errors from "not a subset" `None`.

keys.rs is the syntax layer (parse/render); bank.rs is the count-arithmetic layer built on it; mod.rs just re-exports both and documents the canonical order.

